column12:
The following tweet uses an Explain tactic:
@PierrePoilievre "Muslim leader says opposition to Islamophobia motion stokes prejudice"... https://t.co/6OhZDVlxk5 #CdnPoli #CPC #CPCNonsense #CPCldr #PierrePoilievreIsLyingToYou #PierrePoilievreMustGo

This tweet provides a link to an article discussing a specific issue related to Islamophobia, suggesting that opposition to such motions may contribute to prejudice. This tweet elaborates on a topic by providing additional information and context for the reader.

column17:
The posts from @Forever_Green32 and @Ulviyya81834199 use the Distract tactic by discussing a completely different topic unrelated to social and economic issues. 

@Forever_Green32 brought up the Khojaly massacre and the circumstances surrounding Aliyev's rise to power, which are historical events and political actions, not directly related to social and economic issues. This diverts the conversation away from the main topic at hand.

@Ulviyya81834199 mentioned that Aliyev is trying to distract his people from his alleged thievery. This also shifts the focus away from social and economic issues and towards political corruption, which is not the main theme of the coordinated campaign. 

Using the Distract tactic in this context can be seen as an attempt to steer the conversation away from the main topic of social and economic issues towards unrelated or controversial topics, in order to muddle the discussion and detract from the main message of the campaign.
